"Hughes D.A., Kingston D.G., Todd M.C.","Uncertainty in water resources availability in the Okavango River basin as a result of climate change",2011,"Hydrology and Earth System Sciences","15","3",,"931","941",,,10.5194/hess-15-931-2011,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952849579&partnerID=40&md5=95bad759d3c3512aec1751ea0d8eb1a8","Institute for Water Research, Rhodes University, Grahamstown, South Africa; Department of Geography, University of Otago, P.O. Box 56, Dunedin, New Zealand; Department of Geography, University of Sussex, Brighton, United Kingdom","Hughes, D.A., Institute for Water Research, Rhodes University, Grahamstown, South Africa; Kingston, D.G., Department of Geography, University of Otago, P.O. Box 56, Dunedin, New Zealand; Todd, M.C., Department of Geography, University of Sussex, Brighton, United Kingdom","This paper assesses the hydrological response to scenarios of climate change in the Okavango River catchment in Southern Africa. Climate scenarios are constructed representing different changes in global mean temperature from an ensemble of 7 climate models assessed in the IPCC AR4. The results show a substantial change in mean flow associated with a global warming of 2 °C. However, there is considerable uncertainty in the sign and magnitude of the projected changes between different climate models, implying that the ensemble mean is not an appropriate generalised indicator of impact. The uncertainty in response between different climate model patterns is considerably greater than the range due to uncertainty in hydrological model parameterisation. There is also a clear need to evaluate the physical mechanisms associated with the model projected changes in this region. The implications for water resource management policy are considered. © Author(s) 2011.",,"Climate scenarios; Global-mean temperature; Hydrological models; Hydrological response; Mean flow; Parameterisation; Physical mechanism; River basins; River catchment; Water resources availability; Waterresource management; Catchments; Global warming; Rating; Water management; Climate models; climate change; climate effect; climate modeling; ensemble forecasting; environmental policy; flow modeling; hydrological modeling; hydrological response; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; river basin; uncertainty analysis; water management; water resource; Okavango Basin",,,,,,"Allen, R.G., Pereira, L.S., Raes, D., Smith, M., Crop evapotranspiration - Guidelines for computing crop water requirements (1998) FAO Irrigation and Drainage Paper 56, , FAO, Rome; Andersson, L., Gumbricht, T., Hughes, D., Kniveton, D., Ringrose, S., Savenije, H., Todd, M., Wolski, P., Water flow dynamics in the Okavango River Basin and Delta - A prerequisite for the ecosystems of the Delta (2003) Physics and Chemistry of the Earth, 28 (20-27), pp. 1165-1172. , DOI 10.1016/j.pce.2003.09.002; Andersson, L., Wilk, J., Todd, M.C., Hughes, D.A., Earle, A., Kniveton, D., Layberry, R., Savenije, H.H.G., Impact of climate change and development scenarios on flow patterns in the Okavango River (2006) Journal of Hydrology, 331 (1-2), pp. 43-57. , DOI 10.1016/j.jhydrol.2006.04.039, PII S0022169406002526; Biasutti, M., Held, I.M., Sobel, A.H., Giannini, G., SST forcings and sahel rainfall variability in simulations of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries (2008) J. Climate, 21, pp. 3471-3486; Beven, K., A manifesto for the equifinalty thesis (2006) J. Hydrol., 320, pp. 18-36; Beven, K., Freer, J., Equifinality, data assimilation, and uncertainty estimation in mechanistic modelling of complex environmental systems using the GLUE methodology (2001) Journal of Hydrology, 249 (1-4), pp. 11-29. , DOI 10.1016/S0022-1694(01)00421-8, PII S0022169401004218; Ellery, W.N., McCarthy, T.S., Principles for the sustainable utilization of the Okavango Delta ecosystem, Botswana (1994) Biological Conservation, 70 (2), pp. 159-168. , DOI 10.1016/0006-3207(94)90284-4; Folwell, S., Farqhua